<paper id="1966449987"><title>Communicating processes with value-passing and assignments</title><year>1993</year><authors><author org="University of Sussex, Farmer, UK" id="2094873031">Matthew Hennessy</author><author org="University of Sussex, Farmer, UK" id="1982231962">Anna Ingólfsdóttir</author></authors><n_citation>20</n_citation><doc_type>Journal</doc_type><references><reference>1566845923</reference><reference>1579468405</reference><reference>1883772204</reference><reference>1977542171</reference><reference>2024873396</reference><reference>2073981447</reference><reference>2102097307</reference><reference>2110425399</reference><reference>2131377110</reference><reference>2136920408</reference><reference>2137865376</reference><reference>2157144873</reference><reference>2294826973</reference></references><venue id="128250343" type="J">Formal Aspects of Computing</venue><doi>10.1007/BF01212486</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.46754">Programming language</keyword><keyword weight="0.4582">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.51948">Axiom</keyword><keyword weight="0.57761">Imperative programming</keyword><keyword weight="0.55494">occam</keyword><keyword weight="0.46346">Theoretical computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.55931">Equivalence (measure theory)</keyword><keyword weight="0.55588">Semantic theory of truth</keyword><keyword weight="0.0">Value passing</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer</publisher><abstract>A semantic theory of an imperative language which allows value-passing and assignments as a simple action prefixing is described. Three different semantic approaches are given: denotational based on the mathematical model Acceptance Trees, axiomatic based on inequations and behavioural in terms of testing. The equivalence of these different approaches is shown. The results are compared with similar results for other languages such asCSP andOccam.</abstract></paper>